---
import Callout from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/Callout.astro";
import CodeBlock from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/CodeBlock.astro";
import ContentSection from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/ContentSection.astro";
import PropsTable from "@luciodale/docs-ui-kit/components/PropsTable.astro";
import DocsPage from "../../layouts/DocsPage.astro";
import { href } from "../../lib/link";

export const prerender = true;
---

<DocsPage
	title="Filtering"
	description="How search filtering works: match strategies, search keys, and debouncing."
>
	<ContentSection label="The problem" id="the-problem">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4">
			Search filtering sounds simple until you have real users. Some type the exact name. Some
			type the first few letters. Some type a word from the middle. Some type acronyms. A
			rigid exact-match filter breaks for most of them.
		</p>
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4">
			On the performance side, filtering 100k+ items on every keystroke can freeze the UI if
			you are not careful. The library handles both problems: flexible match strategies via
			match-sorter and optional debouncing to keep things smooth.
		</p>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Filter types" id="filter-types">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4">
			The <code>filterType</code> prop controls how aggressively the search matches. It maps
			directly to match-sorter ranking thresholds. The default is <code>CONTAINS</code>, which
			matches anywhere in the string.
		</p>

		<PropsTable
			title="Available filter types"
			rows={[
				{ name: "CASE_SENSITIVE_EQUAL", type: "Ranking", description: "Exact match, case-sensitive. 'London' matches 'London' but not 'london'." },
				{ name: "EQUAL", type: "Ranking", description: "Exact match, case-insensitive. 'london' matches 'London'." },
				{ name: "STARTS_WITH", type: "Ranking", description: "Matches from the start. 'lon' matches 'London' but not 'Babylon'." },
				{ name: "WORD_STARTS_WITH", type: "Ranking", description: "Any word can match from its start. 'yor' matches 'New York'." },
				{ name: "CONTAINS", type: "Ranking", description: "Matches anywhere in the string. 'ond' matches 'London'. This is the default." },
				{ name: "ACRONYM", type: "Ranking", description: "Matches against first letters of words. 'ny' matches 'New York'." },
				{ name: "MATCHES", type: "Ranking", description: "Most permissive. Matches individual characters in order." },
				{ name: "NO_MATCH", type: "Ranking", description: "Nothing matches. Useful to disable filtering temporarily." },
			]}
		/>

		<CodeBlock
			code={`<SearchableDropdown
  options={cities}
  value={city}
  setValue={setCity}
  filterType="STARTS_WITH"
  placeholder="Type the first letters..."
/>`}
			language="tsx"
			filename="StartsWithExample.tsx"
		/>

		<Callout type="tip" title="Choosing a filter type">
			<p>
				Start with <code>CONTAINS</code> (the default). It works well for most cases. Switch
				to <code>STARTS_WITH</code> if your list has many similar items and you want more
				precise results. Use <code>ACRONYM</code> for lists where users commonly use
				abbreviations.
			</p>
		</Callout>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Search option keys" id="search-option-keys">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4">
			When your options are objects, <code>searchOptionKeys</code> tells the filter which
			fields to search against. It defaults to <code>["label"]</code> for object options,
			so basic search works out of the box. Pass additional keys to search more fields.
		</p>

		<CodeBlock
			code={`type Product = {
  label: string;
  value: string;
  category: string;
  sku: string;
};

// Works without searchOptionKeys — searches "label" by default
<SearchableDropdown
  options={products}
  value={product}
  setValue={setProduct}
  placeholder="Search products..."
/>

// Search by name and category, but not by SKU
<SearchableDropdown
  options={products}
  value={product}
  setValue={setProduct}
  searchOptionKeys={["label", "category"]}
  placeholder="Search products..."
/>`}
			language="tsx"
			filename="SearchKeysExample.tsx"
		/>

		<p class="text-white/60 mt-4 mb-4">
			The type system ensures <code>searchOptionKeys</code> only accepts keys that exist on
			your option type. If you add a field to your type later, it becomes available as a
			search key automatically. If you remove one that's referenced, TypeScript catches it.
		</p>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Debouncing" id="debouncing">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4">
			For small option lists (under a few thousand), filtering is instant and debouncing is
			unnecessary. For very large lists (100k+), debouncing prevents the filter from running
			on every keystroke.
		</p>

		<CodeBlock
			code={`// No debounce (default) — good for small lists
<SearchableDropdown
  options={smallList}
  value={value}
  setValue={setValue}
  debounceDelay={0}
/>

// 100ms debounce — good for large lists
<SearchableDropdown
  options={hugeList}
  value={value}
  setValue={setValue}
  debounceDelay={100}
/>`}
			language="tsx"
			filename="DebounceExample.tsx"
		/>

		<Callout type="info" title="useDeferredValue">
			<p>
				The library also uses React's <code>useDeferredValue</code> internally to keep the
				search input responsive even during heavy filtering. This means typing never lags,
				even with large lists and zero debounce.
			</p>
		</Callout>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Controlled search query" id="controlled-search">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4">
			By default, the search input is uncontrolled. If you need to read or set the search
			query from outside the component, use <code>searchQuery</code> and
			<code>onSearchQueryChange</code>.
		</p>

		<CodeBlock
			code={`function ControlledSearch() {
  const [value, setValue] = useState<string | undefined>(undefined);
  const [query, setQuery] = useState<string | undefined>(undefined);

  return (
    <>
      <p>Current search: {query ?? "none"}</p>
      <SearchableDropdown
        options={cities}
        value={value}
        setValue={setValue}
        searchQuery={query}
        onSearchQueryChange={setQuery}
        placeholder="Search..."
      />
    </>
  );
}`}
			language="tsx"
			filename="ControlledSearchExample.tsx"
		/>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Create new option" id="create-new">
		<p class="text-white/60 mb-4">
			When the search query doesn't match any option, the dropdown shows a "no match" entry
			by default. If <code>createNewOptionIfNoMatch</code> is true (the default), selecting
			that entry creates a new option from the search text.
		</p>

		<CodeBlock
			code={`// Disable new option creation
<SearchableDropdown
  options={cities}
  value={city}
  setValue={setCity}
  createNewOptionIfNoMatch={false}
  dropdownOptionNoMatchLabel="Nothing found"
/>`}
			language="tsx"
			filename="NoCreateExample.tsx"
		/>
	</ContentSection>

	<ContentSection label="Next steps" id="next-steps">
		<ul class="text-white/60 space-y-2 list-disc list-inside">
			<li><a href={href("/docs/styling")} class="text-accent hover:underline">Styling</a> — customize the look and feel</li>
			<li><a href={href("/docs/multi-select")} class="text-accent hover:underline">Multi Select</a> — multi-select specific behavior</li>
			<li><a href={href("/demo/single-select")} class="text-accent hover:underline">Live demo</a> — try filtering on 100k+ options</li>
		</ul>
	</ContentSection>
</DocsPage>
